         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ Is it not a pity to exclude Laurineae from the higher Calyciflorae. — Only when the monochlamydeous plants are reduced to Gymnogens &amp; Amentaceae we can hope to establish a true system of affinity, ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">65.00.00c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To [George Bentham]</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 14.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation: 'vol. iii', i.e. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3, probably an archivist's note when arranging the MSS for binding. The correspondent is most likely to have been Bentham, as M wrote such short notes to him during preparation of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis</seg>. Item dated to early 1865 from the reference to J. Hooker purchasing dissecting instruments for M. They were requested in M to J. Hooker, 25 June 1864 (in this edition as 64-06-25a) and receipt was acknowledged in M to J. Hooker, 22 December 1864.</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Is it not a pity to exclude <name key="Laurineae">Laurineae</name> from the higher <name key="Calyciflorae">Calyciflorae</name>. — Only when the monochlamydeous plants are reduced to <name key="Gymnogen">Gymnogen</name>s &amp; <name key="Amentaceae">Amentaceae</name> we can hope to establish a true system of affinity,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See Maroske (2006) for an analysis of M's views on systems of classification.</p>
               </note> and this will probably be the arrangement I shall adopt for the "Plants of Victoria"</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Melaleuca%20ericifolia">Melaleuca ericifolia</name> is the plant here usually employed for making garlands to decorate public buildings with festoons &amp;c. This may be worthy of notice in the work.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">This use was not mentioned in the entry in <seg style="">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 3, p. 159.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The draft transmitted will liquidate my account, also £1 paid by Dr Hooker for dissecting instruments; the rest can go towards future payments on genera plantarum.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
